To this I answer that a fair and full examination of Cicero’s letters shows that he did look on Pompeius as the champion of the Republic, while Caesar was its declared foe; and that it is unfair to set against the prevailing tone of the letters the hasty expression of a momentary fear, the severish cutburst of distracted petulance.
